<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Active While Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        The Event Point is active only while the trigger condition remains true. When the condition becomes false, the Event Point becomes inactive.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Active While Listening Mode Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> creates conditional, temporary states that are active only as long as
        the trigger condition is true. When the condition becomes false, the Event Point becomes inactive.
        This is used for continuous states like being inside an area, holding an item, or being in a vehicle
        where later logic should stop being true when the condition stops.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The Event Point can toggle between active and inactive repeatedly as the trigger condition changes.
        For example, a <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger with <Bold>Active While</Bold> is active while the player
        is inside the radius and inactive when outside. If the player enters and leaves the radius multiple
        times, the Event Point activates and deactivates each time.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Active While when the Event Point should be active only as long as the trigger condition is true. This is appropriate for temporary states, area-based effects, and conditional logic that should deactivate when the player leaves or the condition changes.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        When To Use Active While
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> when the Event Point should be active only as long as the trigger
        condition is true. This is appropriate for:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,8">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Area messages</Bold> - Show a message while the player is in a specific area</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Continuous effects</Bold> - Camera shake, sound loops, or visual effects that should stop when the trigger stops</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Temporary buffs</Bold> - Power-ups or status effects that last only while a condition is true</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conditional dependencies</Bold> - Event Points that depend on this one should deactivate when this one deactivates</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>State checks</Bold> - "While player holds item X, do Y" or "While in vehicle Z, allow W"</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. When the
        condition becomes false, the Event Point becomes inactive. This can happen repeatedly — the Event
        Point toggles between active and inactive based on the trigger condition.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Example:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold>
        listening mode:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters the radius</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point fires, message appears, Event Point becomes active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player leaves the radius</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point becomes inactive, message disappears</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters the radius again</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point becomes active again, message reappears</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Temporary Area Message
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> or <Bold>Cuboid</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold>
        listening mode shows a message while the player is inside the area. When the player leaves, the
        Event Point becomes inactive and the message disappears.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Continuous Camera Shake
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Shake Camera Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold>
        listening mode shakes the camera continuously while a boss attack or machine is active. When the
        triggering Event Point becomes inactive, the shake stops. This is the observed pattern in retail
        Shake Camera Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Conditional Spawn
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        An enemy spawn Event Point with <Bold>Specific Item Held</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active While</Bold>
        would spawn enemies only while the player holds the item. When the player drops the item, the Event
        Point becomes inactive and the enemies despawn (if the Event Point type supports despawning).
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        All retail Shake Camera Event Points use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger with <Bold>Active While</Bold>
        listening mode, shaking the camera continuously while the dependency Event Point is active. Many
        area-based Message Event Points use <Bold>Active While</Bold> to show temporary messages while
        the player is in specific locations.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Important Warnings
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Dependency chain risk:</Run>
                <Run> Active While can break dependency chains if the source Event Point becomes inactive before dependent Event Points fire. If Event Point B depends on Event Point A, and A uses Active While, B will only be active while A's trigger condition is true. When A becomes inactive, B also becomes inactive.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Example of the problem:</Bold>
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point A has Radius trigger with Active While</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point B has Dependency on A with Active listening mode</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters A's radius → A becomes active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>B fires because A is active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player leaves A's radius → A becomes inactive</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>B also becomes inactive because its dependency source is now inactive</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Solution:</Bold> If Event Point B should stay active even after the player leaves the radius,
        use <Bold>Active</Bold> on Event Point A instead of <Bold>Active While</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Comparison With Other Listening Modes
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active While vs Active</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> is active only while the trigger condition is true. <Bold>Active</Bold>
        stays active permanently once triggered. Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> for temporary states. Use
        <Bold>Active</Bold> for permanent progress markers.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active While vs Active Die</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active While</Bold> can toggle on and off repeatedly. <Bold>Active Die</Bold> fires once
        and becomes permanently dead. Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> for reversible conditions. Use
        <Bold>Active Die</Bold> for one-shot actions.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Active While Listening Mode Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Identify the Event Point that should be active only while a condition is true</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the appropriate trigger type (usually Radius, Cuboid, or Dependency)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set Listening Mode to <Bold>Active While</Bold></Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Configure trigger-specific fields</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the Event Point becomes active when the condition is true</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the Event Point becomes inactive when the condition becomes false</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If using as a dependency source, test that dependent Event Points also deactivate when this one deactivates</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify the toggle behavior works correctly if the condition becomes true and false multiple times</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> The Event Point activates when the condition is true, deactivates when the condition is false, and dependent Event Points behave as intended when this Event Point toggles between active and inactive.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
